BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"UNC Chapel Hill": "https://calendar.unc.edu/event/matt-kaplan-talk-booksigning"}
X-SOURCE-ID:unc_chapel_hill
X-SOURCE:UNC Chapel Hill
CATEGORIES:Lectures
DESCRIPTION:This event features Matt Kaplan\, science correspondent for The
  Economist and author of I Told You So! Scientists Who Were Ridiculed\, Exi
 led and Imprisoned… For Being Right. Kaplan will explore how scientific dis
 covery has often been shaped or hindered by social and political forces. He
 ’ll share stories to illuminate why groundbreaking thinkers from the Victor
 ian to the COVID eras have been dismissed and asks the question\, "How can 
 we make the scientific ecosystem better?” \n\nEvent Details \n📅 March 9\, 2
 026 \n⏰ 4:30 PM \n📍 Frank Porter Graham Student Union \n🎓 Counts as a Campu
 s Life Experience (CLE) credit \n🖊️ Reception & Book signing to follow \n\n
 Kaplan will offer insight into: \n\nWhy many of science’s most persistent p
 roblems are centuries old \n\nHow cultural and political dynamics shape sci
 entific progress \n\nWhat students and researchers can do to build a strong
 er scientific future \n\nStories of scientists whose ideas were initially d
 ismissed but ultimately changed the world \n\nThis promises to be an engagi
 ng and energizing event for our campus community across scientific discipli
 nes.\n\nBroken Beakers and Brilliant Minds: Fixing The Machinery of Science
  \n\n  \n\nFrom the energy crisis and feeding eight billion people to defea
 ting cancer and coping with climate change\, humanity faces some rather lar
 ge challenges today. To tackle them\, we need science running like a well-o
 iled machine. Unfortunately\, it has more often resembled a clunky old engi
 ne: loud\, temperamental and prone to breaking down at the worst possible m
 oment. \n\nIt is tempting to blame recent funding cuts for science’s curren
 t woes\, but focusing only on money rather misses the point. Many of scienc
 e’s biggest problems have been around for years\, sometimes centuries. Scie
 ntists have long been criticized\, sidelined or attacked for having ideas t
 hat were too new\, too inconvenient or simply too correct for the people in
  power at the time. Even truly unscientific behaviors\, like character assa
 ssination and fraud\, are not modern inventions… though they do seem to hav
 e enjoyed a recent renaissance. \n\nThe good news is that longstanding prob
 lems are not the same as unsolvable ones. Join Matt Kaplan\, science corres
 pondent at The Economist and author of I Told You So! Scientists Who Were R
 idiculed\, Exiled and Imprisoned… For Being Right\, for a spirited and insi
 ghtful talk on the history of these endemic issues and what we can do to fi
 nally consign them to the scientific scrap heap.
DTEND:20260309T213000Z
DTSTAMP:20260307T022131Z
DTSTART:20260309T203000Z
GEO:35.909991;-79.047621
LOCATION:The Frank Porter Graham Student Union\, Auditorium
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Matt Kaplan Talk & Booksigning
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52135282317139
URL:https://calendar.unc.edu/event/matt-kaplan-talk-booksigning
END:VEVENT
