SUMMARY:AI for Agents Workshop
DESCRIPTION:All Things AI (Live)\n**Every AI agent is a delegation decisio
 n. This workshop teaches you how to make those decisions well.**\n\n[To pu
 rchase tickets\, visit [https://2026.allthingsai.org/register](https://202
 6.allthingsai.org/register) workshop tickets also include access to the Al
 l Things AI conference on March 24th. ***Price increases after Tuesday\, M
 arch 17 so sign-up early and save $100*** ]\n\nMany organizations have exp
 erimented with AI Agents. Far fewer have moved confidently into sustained\
 , responsible execution.\nAs teams progress from early pilots to real-worl
 d deployment\, leaders often encounter the same challenges: impressive pro
 totypes that stall before production\, uncertainty about where agents actu
 ally add value\, late-breaking security and governance concerns\, and misa
 lignment between business and technical stakeholders about what “success
 ” should look like. Too often\, these issues surface only after cost\, c
 omplexity\, or risk have already compounded.\nThis workshop helps leaders 
 make the shift from experimentation to execution—not by pushing agents e
 verywhere\, but by providing a clear blueprint for **when agents make sens
 e\, when they don’t\, and how to make sound decisions when autonomy is o
 n the table**.\n\n***\n\n#### **The Outcome: Better Decisions\, Earlier**\
 n\nBy the end of this session\, participants will have more than an overvi
 ew of AI Agents. They will leave with a **practical decision-making framew
 ork** they can apply immediately to real initiatives.\nYou’ll be able to
 :\n\n* determine whether an agent is appropriate for a given problem—or 
 whether a copilot or traditional automation is the better choice\n* evalua
 te agent proposals with a clear understanding of autonomy\, risk\, and tra
 deoffs\n* anticipate the organizational\, architectural\, and governance f
 actors that separate successful deployments from stalled experiments\n* id
 entify common failure modes early—while they are still inexpensive to ad
 dress\n\nThe result is clearer judgment about **what to delegate to agents
 \, what to constrain\, and what should remain human**.\n\n***\n\n#### **Wh
 at the Blueprint Covers**\n\nIn this intensive workshop\, business and tec
 hnical leaders will work through a practical blueprint for AI Agent succes
 s\, grounded in real-world constraints and leadership realities.\nKey topi
 cs include:\n\n* understanding degrees of agency and how they change cost\
 , risk\, and accountability\n* distinguishing agents from copilots and tra
 ditional automation—and why that distinction matters\n* identifying use 
 cases where agents consistently create value\, and scenarios where they in
 troduce unnecessary fragility\n* recognizing common pitfalls that derail a
 gent initiatives\, from over-delegation to hidden operational complexity\n
 * aligning organizational readiness\, security\, and governance with the l
 evel of autonomy being introduced\n\nParticipants will also receive a high
 -level technical orientation to the AI Agent ecosystem\, including platfor
 ms\, Model Context Protocol (MCP)\, and model selection tradeoffs. This in
 cludes a balanced discussion of the benefits and risks of using Small Lang
 uage Models (SLMs) in agentic workflows\, particularly when autonomy and t
 ool access are involved.\n\n***\n\n#### **What You’ll Leave With**\n\nPa
 rticipants will leave with:\n\n* A clear framework for deciding **if and w
 hen** AI Agents should be used\n* A practical blueprint outlining the cond
 itions required for agent success—and the signals that indicate trouble\
 n* A realistic understanding of the cost\, complexity\, and operational de
 mands of agent-based systems\n* Clear guidance for incorporating security\
 , governance\, and human oversight from the start\n* A shared language tha
 t aligns business and technical leaders around the same decision criteria\
 n\n***\n\n#### **Who This Is For**\n\nThis workshop is designed for busine
 ss and technical leaders responsible for turning AI experimentation into o
 perational reality\, including:\n\n* Leaders driving digital\, AI\, or tra
 nsformation initiatives (e.g.\, Chief Digital Officers\, Heads of AI\, Tra
 nsformation and Digital Strategy leaders)\n* Technology and architecture l
 eaders accountable for execution and scale (e.g.\, CTOs\, CIOs\, VPs of En
 gineering\, Enterprise and Solution Architects)\n* Product and innovation 
 leaders shaping AI-enabled capabilities (e.g.\, CPOs\, Heads of Product\, 
 Innovation and Emerging Technology leaders)\n* Security\, risk\, and gover
 nance leaders involved in overseeing autonomous or AI-driven systems (e.g.
 \, CISOs\, Responsible AI and Risk leaders)\n\nThis session is especially 
 valuable for leaders who sit at the intersection of strategy and execution
 —those expected to decide **when AI Agents should be used\, how much aut
 hority they should have\, and how to govern them responsibly**.\n\n[To pur
 chase tickets\, visit [https://2026.allthingsai.org/register](https://2026
 .allthingsai.org/register) workshop tickets also include access to the All
  Things AI conference on March 24th. ***Price increases after Tuesday\, Ma
 rch 17 so sign-up early and save $100*** ]
