BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"UNC Chapel Hill": "https://calendar.unc.edu/event/the-triangle-best-place-to-live-in-the-us"}
X-SOURCE-ID:unc_chapel_hill
X-SOURCE:UNC Chapel Hill
CATEGORIES:Lectures
DESCRIPTION:This Community Classroom event will be held on March 24\, 2026\
 ; Registration is required to attend.\n\n \n\nWhy are so many people moving
  to the Triangle\, and what does this growth mean for current residents?\n 
 \n\nAcross the country\, rising housing costs and declining economic securi
 ty are reshaping where people can afford to live. In places like California
 \, homeownership is out of reach for educated\, middle-class families.\n \n
 \nThe Raleigh–Durham–Chapel Hill region is now one of the nation’s fastest-
 growing destinations for people who are leaving their current homes in sear
 ch of affordability\, opportunity\, and a better quality of life. This Comm
 unity Classroom presentation explores why the Triangle attracts newcomers\,
  and what that rapid growth means for housing\, consumer costs\, environmen
 tal sustainability\, and a shared sense of place for those who already live
  here.\n \n\nDrawing on research and lived experience\, this free presentat
 ion examines multiple sides of this story. It considers the benefits migran
 ts find here\, the concerns they bring\, and increasingly heated debates ov
 er development and growth. As newcomers engage in local politics\, the regi
 on faces critical questions about current and future population expansion.\
 n \n\nCan the Triangle grow without repeating the inequalities and environm
 ental challenges our new neighbors hoped to escape? This conversation on Tu
 esday\, March 24\, 2026 at 6:30 PM invites reflection on how today’s choice
 s will shape the region for generations. \n\n \n\nAbout the Presenter\n\nNi
 na Martin\, PhD\, is an urban geographer focused on how cities grow\, chang
 e\, and address inequality. Her research links urban planning and public po
 licy with housing\, economic development\, and labor markets. She is partic
 ularly interested in how “progressive” cities can unintentionally reproduce
  the very inequities they aim to solve.\n \n\nShe teaches urban geography a
 nd globalization courses at UNC–Chapel Hill. She also serves as Director of
  Research Curricula in the Office of Undergraduate Research\, supporting in
 terdisciplinary research by students and faculty. Additionally\, Dr. Martin
  serves on the Durham Workers’ Rights Commission\, advising the City Counci
 l on issues affecting working people.\n \n\nDr. Martin earned a PhD from th
 e University of Illinois at Chicago. She holds an MSc from the London Schoo
 l of Economics\, and received her BA from McGill University in Montreal.
DTSTAMP:20260307T022131Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260324
GEO:35.899895;-79.012764
LOCATION:William and Ida Friday Center
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:The Triangle: Best Place to Live in the U.S.?
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52258390275704
URL:https://calendar.unc.edu/event/the-triangle-best-place-to-live-in-the-u
 s
END:VEVENT
