BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"UNC Chapel Hill": "https://calendar.unc.edu/event/mfa-2026-thesis-exhibitions-at-lump-gallery"}
X-SOURCE-ID:unc_chapel_hill
X-SOURCE:UNC Chapel Hill
CATEGORIES:Exhibits
DESCRIPTION:Department of Art and Art History\n\n \n\nLump Presents: UNC-Ch
 apel Hill MFA Thesis Exhibitions \n\nMarch 6th - March 29th:\n\nINFRA ULTRA
  by CJ Murphy / Under the Thumb by Michelle Lisa Polissaint\n\nOpening rece
 ption: March 6\, 6-9 pm\n\n \n\nApril 3rd - April 26th:\n\nNepantla by Wend
 y Yamilett Moran / Growing Elsewhere: Ghorbatī (غربتی) by Rojano Mohammadza
 deh / Blood\, Sap\, Dirt by Iris Moyan Wang\n\nOpening reception: April 3\,
  6-9 pm\n\nLump Gallery is located at 505 S. Blount St.\, Raleigh\, NC 2760
 1\n\nOpening Hours: Saturdays and Sundays\, 1-5 pm\, and by appointment.\n\
 n \n\nLump Gallery is pleased to present thesis exhibitions by UNC-Chapel H
 ill’s 2026 MFA graduating class. \n\n \n\nAt the conclusion of a rigorous\,
  research-based two-year program\, these artists consider the concept of pl
 ace and their personal relationships to it. Each artist employs a range of 
 media and responds to geographic\, constructed\, technological\, and bodily
  autonomy. These relationships between place and personal narrative raise b
 roader questions around positionality and society\; communication and ident
 ity\; and human impact. Revelation\, purpose\, and possibility guide each a
 rtist’s research-centered practices.\n\n \n\nCJ Murphy creates works that r
 ender the intersection of technology\, magic\, and globalization material b
 y reinvigorating found and discarded electrical waste. Michelle Lisa Poliss
 aint draws on her experience in a strict religious community and deep resea
 rch into the BITE method to discuss contemporary issues of indoctrination\,
  high-control groups\, and authoritarianism. Rojano Mohammadzadeh draws on 
 Islamic prayer\, talismanic imagery\, text\, and ritualized gestures to app
 roach the immigrant experience through what she terms transplantation: surv
 ival through negotiating acceptance within a host body. Wendy Yamilett Morá
 n’s practice explores the intersections of culture\, realism\, and spiritua
 lity through painting and ceramics\, using their work to examine how identi
 ty\, memory\, and belonging are shaped within in-between spaces. Iris Moyan
  Wang is an interdisciplinary artist working primarily with ink painting an
 d ceramics to create fluid and erotic hybridizations of bodies and botanica
 ls that reimagine Chinese cultural heritage.\n\n \n\nFor press inquiries or
  other questions\, please contact uncmfathesis@yahoo.com
DTEND:20260420T010000Z
DTSTAMP:20260307T022132Z
DTSTART:20260419T220000Z
GEO:35.773769;-78.636571
LOCATION:Lump Gallery/Projects
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:MFA 2026 Thesis Exhibitions at Lump Gallery
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52241621295051
URL:https://calendar.unc.edu/event/mfa-2026-thesis-exhibitions-at-lump-gall
 ery
END:VEVENT
