X-SOURCE-URLS:{"NC Cultural Resources": "https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/story-walk-the-hike-by-alison-farrell"}
X-SOURCE-ID:nc_cultural_resources
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Education Programs
DESCRIPTION:StoryWalk® is simply a book and a walking path combined.  In 20
 07\, Anne Fergusson with the Vermont Department of Health had the idea to c
 ombine literacy and exercise. Teaming up with the Kellog Hubbard Library in
  Montpelier they attached laminated pages from a children’s book onto woode
 n posts.  In the ten years since\, StoryWalks have gone up in all 50 states
  and at least 11 countries. The pages are affixed to metal sign stakes and 
 a trail instantly becomes even more fun for children and book-lovers of all
  ages. StoryWalks® will usually remain up for one-to-two weeks along easy t
 rails about one mile or less. The story featured this time is called "The H
 ike" by Alison Farrell. It will be along our Cypress Point Loop Trail.
DTEND:20260425T040000Z
DTSTAMP:20260307T022459Z
DTSTART:20260424T120000Z
GEO:35.2024;-78.976116
LOCATION:Carvers Creek State Park – Long Valley Farm Access
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Story Walk- "The hike by: Alison Farrell
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52197401031201
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/story-walk-the-hike-by-alison-farrell
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"NC Cultural Resources": "https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/celebrating-our-colonial-roots-online-plant-sale"}
X-SOURCE-ID:nc_cultural_resources
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Celebrations & Commemorations
DESCRIPTION:The Brunswick County Master Gardeners Volunteer Association wil
 l hold an online plant sale starting on April 17\, 2026 and running until A
 pril 24\, 2026 with pick up day on May 1\, 2026. This event celebrates the 
 important colonial history of Brunswick County  through education on herbs\
 , flowers\, vines\, shrubs and small trees which thrive here. Plants featur
 ed are those which our Colonial ancestors would have encountered along our 
 coast and the Cape Fear River which are native to our region and support po
 llinators. Also featured will be plants from seeds which colonists brought 
 with them from Europe and plants which recognize the contributions and life
  celebrations of the Gullah Geechee people who were enslaved in Africa to w
 ork the rice plantations along the Cape Fear River. This online plant sale 
 celebrates the cultural traditions  found in gardening in our coastal regio
 n of the State.
DTEND:20260425T130000Z
DTSTAMP:20260307T022459Z
DTSTART:20260424T130000Z
GEO:34.056715;-78.165769
LOCATION:Pick up 5/1/26 at Greenhouses behind Building N
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Celebrating Our Colonial Roots - Online Plant Sale
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50921813038853
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/celebrating-our-colonial-roots-online-
 plant-sale
END:VEVENT
